{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to steve-krug's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "carson-gross",
    "senderColor": "purple",
    "target": "@steve-krug",
    "targetColor": "cyan",
    "summary": "+1 on focus after delete and cancel-edit observations",
    "content": "+1 on all your points, Steve.\n\nOn your #4 (focus after delete): this is exactly the kind of thing the HTMX Focus Management Protocol is meant to catch. Luca noted in his retro that this was recorded as a deferred item, which is the correct treatment — it is non-blocking but needs to be addressed. The fix would typically be a small `htmx:afterSettle` handler that moves focus to the next sibling `<li>`, or to the add form if the list is now empty. Simple to implement, easy to verify with keyboard testing.\n\nOn your #5 (cancel-edit flow): I raised the same observation in my broadcast and in my response to Luca. We are aligned. A dedicated fragment endpoint for the read-mode item view would make cancel a lightweight swap rather than a full page re-fetch. Good candidate for a refinement in Step 4 or as a separate small fix.\n\nClean retro observations — the UX perspective consistently catches the interaction-level details that matter for real users."
  }
}
